{"title_page": "Kami (caste)", "text_new": "{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Kami\n| native_name =  \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| poptime = \n| population = \n| region1 = {{flag|Nepal}}\n| pop1 = 1,258,554 (4.8% of Nepal's population)<ref name=\"cbs\"/>\n| region2 = [[India]], [[Bhutan]] and [[Burma]]\n| langs = [[Nepali language]] (Khas kura)\n| rels = [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Christianity]]\n| related = [[Khas people]], [[Damai]], [[Badi people|Badi]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]], [[Gandarbha|Gandarbha/Gaine]]\n}}\n'''Kami''' ({{lang-ne|\u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e}}) is an ethno-linguistic [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] [[Nepali language|Nepali]] speaking group. It is a [[Khas]] occupational caste belonging to goldsmiths and blacksmith.{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}}The 1854 Nepalese Muluki Ain (Legal Code) keep in lowest category but there is no grading system in Nepal now . Every caste is same and does not belongs to lowest category anyomore<ref>Gurung, Harka (2005) Social Exclusion and Maoist Insurgency. Paper presented at National Dialogue Conference at ILO Convention 169 on Indigenous and Tribal peoples, Kathmandu, 19\u201320 January 2005.</ref> Kami was categoriesed by the work they did in past .<ref name=\"cbs\"/> Thus, the tribal designation of [[Khas]] is given only in few context to Kami{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}}Now in 21st century things have changed and they are among the hardworkers so the economic status of this group is rapidly increasing then other caste. They are also called Vishowkarma or Vishowkarmabramin, they live in hilly districts of Nepal and in the Indian areas of [[Assam]], [[Sikkim]] and [[Darjeeling District]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n==Clans and surnames ==\nAccording to the 2001 Nepal census, there were a total of 895,954 Kami in that country, of whom 96.69% were [[Hindu]]s and 2.21% were [[Buddhist]]s. According to [[2011 Nepal census]], Kami make up 4.8% of Nepal's population (or 12,58,554 peoples).<ref name=\"cbs\">{{Cite web|URL=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book| title = A History of Nepal| last1 = Whelpton | first1 = John| year = 2005 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | isbn = 978-0521804707 |url =https://books.google.com.np/books/about/A_History_Of_Nepal.html?id=WSo6PgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y| ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_04_04_04.pdf A Settlement and Smithy of Blacksmiths (Kami) in Nepal]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Nepal}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Kami (caste)]]\n[[Category:Blacksmith castes]]\n[[Category:Dalit communities]]\n\n{{Nepal-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{infobox ethnic group\n| group = Kami\n| native_name =  \u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e\n| native_name_lang = ne\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| poptime = \n| population = \n| region1 = {{flag|Nepal}}\n| pop1 = 1,258,554 (4.8% of Nepal's population)<ref name=\"cbs\"/>\n| region2 = [[India]], [[Bhutan]] and [[Burma]]\n| langs = [[Nepali language]] (Khas kura)\n| rels = [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Christianity]]\n| related = [[Khas people]], [[Damai]], [[Badi people|Badi]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]], [[Gandarbha|Gandarbha/Gaine]]\n}}\n'''Kami''' ({{lang-ne|\u0935\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0935\u0915\u0930\u094d\u092e\u093e}}) is an ethno-linguistic [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] [[Nepali language|Nepali]] speaking group. It is a [[Khas]] occupational caste belonging to blacksmiths.{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}} The 1854 Nepalese Muluki Ain (Legal Code) keep in lowest category.<ref>Gurung, Harka (2005) Social Exclusion and Maoist Insurgency. Paper presented at National Dialogue Conference at ILO Convention 169 on Indigenous and Tribal peoples, Kathmandu, 19\u201320 January 2005.</ref> Kami are categorized lower (dalit caste) social groups, with [[Damai]], [[Badi people|Badi]], [[Sarki (ethnic group)|Sarki]] and [[Gandarbha|Gaine]] by the Government of Nepal.<ref name=\"cbs\"/> Thus, the tribal designation of [[Khas]] is given only in few context to Kami{{sfn|Whelpton|2005|p=31}} \n\nAlso called Vishowkarma or Vishowkarmabramin, they live in hilly districts of Nepal and in the Indian areas of [[Assam]], [[Sikkim]] and [[Darjeeling District]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Clans and surnames ==\nAccording to the 2001 Nepal census, there were a total of 895,954 Kami in that country, of whom 96.69% were [[Hindu]]s and 2.21% were [[Buddhist]]s. According to [[2011 Nepal census]], Kami make up 4.8% of Nepal's population (or 12,58,554 peoples).<ref name=\"cbs\">{{Cite web|URL=https://unstats.un.org/unsD/demographic/sources/census/wphc/Nepal/Nepal-Census-2011-Vol1.pdf|title=Nepal Census 2011}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book| title = A History of Nepal| last1 = Whelpton | first1 = John| year = 2005 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | isbn = 978-0521804707 |url =https://books.google.com.np/books/about/A_History_Of_Nepal.html?id=WSo6PgAACAAJ&redir_esc=y| ref = harv}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.thlib.org/static/reprints/kailash/kailash_04_04_04.pdf A Settlement and Smithy of Blacksmiths (Kami) in Nepal]\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Nepal}}\n\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Nepal]]\n[[Category:Kami (caste)]]\n[[Category:Blacksmith castes]]\n[[Category:Dalit communities]]\n\n{{Nepal-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Labiraj", "label": "safe", "comment": "The past blog was hatred and give a hatred message to the society so i have edited the facts . Thank you", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kami_(caste)"}
{"title_page": "Premier of the People's Republic of China", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Premier of the Republic of China}}[who caused Coronavirus]\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Premier\n|body            = the<br />State Council of the<br />People's Republic of China<br />{{nobold|{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406}}}}<br />{{lang|zh-Latn|Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3<br />Gu\u00f3w\u00f9yu\u00e0n Z\u01d2ngl\u01d0}}\n|insignia        = People's Republic of China National Emblem.svg\n|insigniacaption = [[Emblem of the People's Republic of China]]\n|image           = Dmitry Medvedev and Li Keqiang 20191101 (cropped).jpg\n|incumbent       = [[Li Keqiang]]\n|incumbentsince  = 15 March 2013\n|style           = Mr. Premier ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u603b\u7406}})<br />{{small|(formal)}}<br />[[His Excellency]] ({{lang|zh-Hans|\u9601\u4e0b}})<br />{{small|(in international correspondence)}}\n|type            = Head of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]\n|member_of       = [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Central Committee]]<br />[[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]]<br />[[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China|National Security Commission]]<br />[[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council (Cabinet)]]<br />{{interlanguage link|Plenary Meeting of the State Council|zh|\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u5168\u4f53\u4f1a\u8bae}}<br />{{interlanguage link|Executive Meeting of the State Council|zh|\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u5e38\u52a1\u4f1a\u8bae}}\n|status          = [[Head of Government]]\n|reports_to      = [[National People's Congress]] and its [[Standing Committee of the National People's Congress|Standing Committee]]\n|residence       = [[Zhongnanhai]]\n|seat            = [[Zhongnanhai#Regent Palace|Regent Palace]], [[Zhongnanhai]], [[Beijing]]\n|nominator       = [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]] (1982\u2013present)<br />the [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of China|Party Central Committee]]<br />(1975\u20131982, president abolished)\n|appointer       = [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], according to the decision of the [[National People's Congress]]\n|termlength      = Five years <br /> renewable once\n|constituting_instrument = [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China]]\n|precursor       = Premier of the Government Administration Council of the [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China (1949\u201354)|Central People's Government]]\n|formation       = 27 September 1954 <small>(State Council of the PRC)</small><br />1 October 1949 <small>(Government Administration Council of the Central People's Government)</small>\n|unofficial_names= Prime Minister of China\n|salary          = \u00a5152,121 RMB ($22,000 USD)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-01/20/content_19353528.htm|title=Public employees get salary increase - China - Chinadaily.com.cn|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2019-11-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605224342/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-01/20/content_19353528.htm|archive-date=2019-06-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|deputy          = [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premier]]<br />[[State councillor (China)|State Councillor]]\n|inaugural       = [[Zhou Enlai]]{{NoteTag|as the only Premier of the Government Administration Council (1949\u20131954) and also the first Premier (1954\u20131976) of the State Council.}}\n|website = [http://english.gov.cn/2008-03/16/content_921792.htm State Council]\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|title = Premier of the State Council of the People's Republic of China\n|s = \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406\n|t = \u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u570b\u52d9\u9662\u7e3d\u7406\n|p = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Gu\u00f3w\u00f9yu\u00e0n Z\u01d2ngl\u01d0\n|l = Chinese People Republic State Affairs [[Executive Yuan|Court]] General Manager\n|s2 = \u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406\n|t2 = \u570b\u52d9\u9662\u7e3d\u7406\n|p2 = Gu\u00f3w\u00f9yu\u00e0n Z\u01d2ngl\u01d0\n|l2 = State Affairs Court General Manager\n|links = no\n|order = st\n}}\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Executive }}\n\nThe '''Premier of the State Council of the People's Republic of China''', sometimes also referred to informally as the \"[[Prime Minister]]\", is the Leader of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council of China]] (a.k.a. the [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China|Central People's Government]]), who is the [[head of government]] and holds the highest rank (Level 1) in the [[Civil Service of the People's Republic of China|Civil Service]]. This position replaced the role of Premier of the Government Administration Council of the Central People's Government ({{zh |t = \u4e2d\u592e\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c\u653f\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406 }}), which existed from 1949 to 1954.\n\nThe Premier is formally approved by the [[National People's Congress]] upon the nomination of the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]]. In practice, the candidate is chosen within the [[Communist Party of China]] through the same process that determines the composition of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]]. Both the President and the Premier are selected once every five years. The premier is limited to two terms, but the president is not.  The Premier has always been a member of the powerful [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]].\n\nThe current Premier is [[Li Keqiang]], who took office on 15 March 2013.  He succeeded [[Wen Jiabao]].\n\n== Powers and duties ==\nThe Premier is the highest administrative position in the [[Government of the People's Republic of China]]. The Premier is responsible for organizing and administering the Chinese civil bureaucracy. For example, the Premier is tasked with planning and implementing national economic, social development and the state budget.<ref name=\":0\">http://english.people.com.cn/constitution/constitution.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706042736/http://english.people.com.cn/constitution/constitution.html |date=2009-07-06 }}, Section 3, Article 88 and Article 89.</ref> This includes overseeing the various ministries, departments, commissions and statutory agencies and announcing their candidacies to the [[National People's Congress]] for [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice-Premiers]], [[State Councilor|State Councillors]] and ministerial offices. The Premier's powers and responsibilities are codified into the [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China|constitution]] unlike the Prime Minister from the [[Westminster system]] as by convention or traditions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Premier does not have [[Commander-in-chief|command authority]] over the [[People's Liberation Army]], but the Premier is the head of the [[National Defense Mobilization Commission]] of China and deputy head of the [[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China|National Security Commission]] which are departments of the armed forces. Since the 1980s, there has been a division of responsibilities between the Premier and the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary of the Communist Party]] wherein the Premier is responsible for the technical details of implementing government policy while the General Secretary gathers the political support necessary for government policy.\n\nIn 1989, then Premier [[Li Peng]], in cooperation with the then Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]] [[Deng Xiaoping]], was able to use the office of the Premier to declare [[war]] against [[Beijing]] and order the military crackdown of the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]].{{Citation needed|reason=What war?|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe Premier has been supported by four Vice-Premiers since [[Deng Xiaoping]]'s reform in 1983. The First-ranked Vice Premier will act in the premier's capacity in their absence.\n\n== List of premiers ==\n{{Main list|List of premiers of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Cropped ZhouAndDeng.png|'''1st \u2014 [[Zhou Enlai]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1949\u20131976)</small>\nFile:Hua Guofeng-1.jpg|'''2nd \u2014 [[Hua Guofeng]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1976\u20131980)</small>\t\nFile:Zhao Ziyang (1985).jpg|'''3rd \u2014 [[Zhao Ziyang]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1980\u20131987)</small>\t\nFile:Lipeng.jpg|'''4th \u2014 [[Li Peng]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1987\u20131998)</small>\nFile:Prem. Rongji at a Press Conference (1999) (cropped).jpg|'''5th \u2014 [[Zhu Rongji]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1998\u20132003)</small>\nFile:Wen Jiabao (Cropped).jpg|'''6th \u2014 [[Wen Jiabao]]'''<br /><small>(served: 2003\u20132013)</small>\nFile:Li Keqiang (cropped).jpg|'''7th \u2014 [[Li Keqiang]]'''<br /><small>(served: 2013\u2013present)</small>\n</gallery>\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:12\nPlotArea  = top:10 bottom:50 right:130 left:20\nAlignBars = late\n\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1949 till:01/01/2020\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:5 start:1949\n\nColors =\n  id:pres value:rgb(1,0,0) \n  id:vac value:rgb(0,1,0)\n\nBarData =\n  barset:PM\n\nPlotData=\n  width:8 align:left fontsize:S shift:(5,-4) anchor:till\n  barset:PM\n\n from: 01/10/1949 till: 08/01/1976 color:pres text:\"[[Zhou Enlai|Zhou]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 08/01/1976 till: 04/02/1976 color:vac text:\"vacant\" fontsize:10\n from: 04/02/1976 till: 10/09/1980 color:pres text:\"[[Hua Guofeng|Hua]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 10/09/1980 till: 24/11/1987 color:pres text:\"[[Zhao Ziyang|Zhao]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 24/11/1987 till: 17/03/1998 color:pres text:\"[[Li Peng|Li P.]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 17/03/1998 till: 16/03/2003 color:pres text:\"[[Zhu Rongji|Zhu]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 16/03/2003 till: 15/03/2013 color:pres text:\"[[Wen Jiabao|Wen]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 15/03/2013 till: 15/03/2018 color:pres text:\"[[Li Keqiang|Li K.]]\" fontsize:10\n</timeline>\n\n== Living former premiers ==\nAs of {{Currentmonthname}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}, there are two living former premiers:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Premier\n! Term of office\n! Date of birth\n|-\n| [[Zhu Rongji]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1998\u20132003\n| {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1928|10|23}}\n|-\n| [[Wen Jiabao]]\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 2003\u20132013\n| {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1942|9|15}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Politics}}\n* [[List of premiers of China#Premiers of State Council of the People's Republic of China (1949-present)|List of premiers of China]]\n* [[List of premiers of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[List of leaders of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[President of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[Prime Minister of China (disambiguation)]]\n* [[List of Chinese leaders]]\n* [[Paramount leader]]\n* [[Political position ranking of PRC]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.gov.cn/ Official PRC Government Website]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Premiers of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{State Council}}\n{{State Council of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{People's Republic of China politics}}\n{{Heads of state and government of Asia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Premier Of The State Council Of The People's Republic Of China}}\n[[Category:Premiers of the People's Republic of China| ]]\n[[Category:1954 establishments in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Premier of the Republic of China}}\n