rty Central Committee]]<br />(1975\u20131982, president abolished)\n|appointer       = [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]], according to the decision of the [[National People's Congress]]\n|termlength      = Five years <br /> renewable once\n|constituting_instrument = [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China]]\n|precursor       = Premier of the Government Administration Council of the [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China (1949\u201354)|Central People's Government]]\n|formation       = 27 September 1954 <small>(State Council of the PRC)</small><br />1 October 1949 <small>(Government Administration Council of the Central People's Government)</small>\n|unofficial_names= Prime Minister of China\n|salary          = \u00a5152,121 RMB ($22,000 USD)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-01/20/content_19353528.htm|title=Public employees get salary increase - China - Chinadaily.com.cn|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2019-11-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605224342/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2015-01/20/content_19353528.htm|archive-date=2019-06-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|deputy          = [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice Premier]]<br />[[State councillor (China)|State Councillor]]\n|inaugural       = [[Zhou Enlai]]{{NoteTag|as the only Premier of the Government Administration Council (1949\u20131954) and also the first Premier (1954\u20131976) of the State Council.}}\n|website = [http://english.gov.cn/2008-03/16/content_921792.htm State Council]\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|title = Premier of the State Council of the People's Republic of China\n|s = \u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406\n|t = \u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u570b\u52d9\u9662\u7e3d\u7406\n|p = Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Gu\u00f3w\u00f9yu\u00e0n Z\u01d2ngl\u01d0\n|l = Chinese People Republic State Affairs [[Executive Yuan|Court]] General Manager\n|s2 = \u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406\n|t2 = \u570b\u52d9\u9662\u7e3d\u7406\n|p2 = Gu\u00f3w\u00f9yu\u00e0n Z\u01d2ngl\u01d0\n|l2 = State Affairs Court General Manager\n|links = no\n|order = st\n}}\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Executive }}\n\nThe '''Premier of the State Council of the People's Republic of China''', sometimes also referred to informally as the \"[[Prime Minister]]\", is the Leader of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council of China]] (a.k.a. the [[Central People's Government of the People's Republic of China|Central People's Government]]), who is the [[head of government]] and holds the highest rank (Level 1) in the [[Civil Service of the People's Republic of China|Civil Service]]. This position replaced the role of Premier of the Government Administration Council of the Central People's Government ({{zh |t = \u4e2d\u592e\u4eba\u6c11\u653f\u5e9c\u653f\u52a1\u9662\u603b\u7406 }}), which existed from 1949 to 1954.\n\nThe Premier is formally approved by the [[National People's Congress]] upon the nomination of the [[President of the People's Republic of China|President]]. In practice, the candidate is chosen within the [[Communist Party of China]] through the same process that determines the composition of the [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]]. Both the President and the Premier are selected once every five years. The premier is limited to two terms, but the president is not.  The Premier has always been a member of the powerful [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]].\n\nThe current Premier is [[Li Keqiang]], who took office on 15 March 2013.  He succeeded [[Wen Jiabao]].\n\n== Powers and duties ==\nThe Premier is the highest administrative position in the [[Government of the People's Republic of China]]. The Premier is responsible for organizing and administering the Chinese civil bureaucracy. For example, the Premier is tasked with planning and implementing national economic, social development and the state budget.<ref name=\":0\">http://english.people.com.cn/constitution/constitution.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706042736/http://english.people.com.cn/constitution/constitution.html |date=2009-07-06 }}, Section 3, Article 88 and Article 89.</ref> This includes overseeing the various ministries, departments, commissions and statutory agencies and announcing their candidacies to the [[National People's Congress]] for [[Vice Premier of the People's Republic of China|Vice-Premiers]], [[State Councilor|State Councillors]] and ministerial offices. The Premier's powers and responsibilities are codified into the [[Constitution of the People's Republic of China|constitution]] unlike the Prime Minister from the [[Westminster system]] as by convention or traditions.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Premier does not have [[Commander-in-chief|command authority]] over the [[People's Liberation Army]], but the Premier is the head of the [[National Defense Mobilization Commission]] of China and deputy head of the [[National Security Commission of the Communist Party of China|National Security Commission]] which are departments of the armed forces. Since the 1980s, there has been a division of responsibilities between the Premier and the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|General Secretary of the Communist Party]] wherein the Premier is responsible for the technical details of implementing government policy while the General Secretary gathers the political support necessary for government policy.\n\nIn 1989, then Premier [[Li Peng]], in cooperation with the then Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]] [[Deng Xiaoping]], was able to use the office of the Premier to declare [[war]] against [[Beijing]] and order the military crackdown of the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989]].{{Citation needed|reason=What war?|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe Premier has been supported by four Vice-Premiers since [[Deng Xiaoping]]'s reform in 1983. The First-ranked Vice Premier will act in the premier's capacity in their absence.\n\n== List of premiers ==\n{{Main list|List of premiers of the People's Republic of China}}\n\n<gallery perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Cropped ZhouAndDeng.png|'''1st \u2014 [[Zhou Enlai]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1949\u20131976)</small>\nFile:Hua Guofeng-1.jpg|'''2nd \u2014 [[Hua Guofeng]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1976\u20131980)</small>\t\nFile:Zhao Ziyang (1985).jpg|'''3rd \u2014 [[Zhao Ziyang]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1980\u20131987)</small>\t\nFile:Lipeng.jpg|'''4th \u2014 [[Li Peng]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1987\u20131998)</small>\nFile:Prem. Rongji at a Press Conference (1999) (cropped).jpg|'''5th \u2014 [[Zhu Rongji]]'''<br /><small>(served: 1998\u20132003)</small>\nFile:Wen Jiabao (Cropped).jpg|'''6th \u2014 [[Wen Jiabao]]'''<br /><small>(served: 2003\u20132013)</small>\nFile:Li Keqiang (cropped).jpg|'''7th \u2014 [[Li Keqiang]]'''<br /><small>(served: 2013\u2013present)</small>\n</gallery>\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:12\nPlotArea  = top:10 bottom:50 right:130 left:20\nAlignBars = late\n\nDateFormat = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod     = from:01/01/1949 till:01/01/2020\nTimeAxis   = orientation:horizontal\nScaleMajor = unit:year increment:5 start:1949\n\nColors =\n  id:pres value:rgb(1,0,0) \n  id:vac value:rgb(0,1,0)\n\nBarData =\n  barset:PM\n\nPlotData=\n  width:8 align:left fontsize:S shift:(5,-4) anchor:till\n  barset:PM\n\n from: 01/10/1949 till: 08/01/1976 color:pres text:\"[[Zhou Enlai|Zhou]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 08/01/1976 till: 04/02/1976 color:vac text:\"vacant\" fontsize:10\n from: 04/02/1976 till: 10/09/1980 color:pres text:\"[[Hua Guofeng|Hua]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 10/09/1980 till: 24/11/1987 color:pres text:\"[[Zhao Ziyang|Zhao]]\" fontsize:10\n from: 24/11/1987 till: 17/03/1998 color:pres text:\"[[Li Peng|Li P.]]\" fontsize:1