{"title_page": "Nankana Sahib District", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nankana Sahib\n| official_name           = \n| native_name             = {{Nastaliq|\u0636\u0650\u0644\u0639 \u0646\u0646\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06c1 \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628}}\n| native_name_lang        =\n| settlement_type         = [[Districts of Pakistan|District]]\n| image_skyline           = Pakistan - Punjab - Nankana Sahib.svg\n| imagesize               =\n| image_walt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_map               =\n| mapsize                 = 300px\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Map of Punjab (white) with Nankana Sahib District (Maroon).\n| coordinates             = {{coord|31.449561|73.70648|type:adm2nd_source:itwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Pakistan]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Pakistan|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = [[Headquarters]]\n| seat           = [[Nankana Sahib]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          = 2960\n| population_as_of        = 2017\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archivedate=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 1,356,374\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone1               = [[Time in Pakistan|PST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5\n| established_title       = Established\n| established_date        = May 2005\n| leader_title            = Hadhrat Khawajah Muhammad Sardar Ahmed Naqshbandi\n| blank_name              = [[Tehsil]]s\n| blank_info              = [[Nankana Sahib]]<br>[[Sangla Hill]]<br>[[Shah Kot Tehsil |Shah Kot]]\n| blank1_name_sec1         = District Council\n| blank1_info_sec1         = \n| demographics1_title1    = Main language(s)\n| demographics1_info1     = Punjabi, Urdu\n| website                 = <!-- DEAD LINK {{URL|http://www.nankana-sahib.gov.pk/|link}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Nankana Sahib District ''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0636\u0650\u0644\u0639 \u0646\u0646\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06c1 \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628}}}})  is a [[Districts of Pakistan|district]] in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province of [[Pakistan]]. [[Nankana Sahib]] is the seat of the district government, and Shahkot<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etcnews.tv/shahkot-punjab-destination-guide-pakistan/|title=SHAHKOT IN PUNJAB DESTINATION GUIDE PAKISTAN|website=www.etcnews.tv|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> is the largest urban center.  The district of Nankana Sahib is located about {{Convert|75|km|mi}} west of [[Lahore]] and about {{Convert|55|km|mi}} east of [[Faisalabad]]. Until 2005, it was part of [[Sheikhupura District]].\n\nAccording to the 1998 census results, the most widely spoken [[first language]]<ref>\"Mother tongue\": defined as the language of communication between parents and children.</ref> in the Nankana Sahib Tehsil was [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], accounting for {{sigfig|98.58|3}}% of the population, while [[Urdu]] was the native language of {{sigfig|0.41|2}}%.<ref>{{Cite book| title = 1998 District Census report of Sheikhupura| location = Islamabad| publisher = Population Census Organization, Statistics Division, Government of Pakistan| series = Census publication | volume =  79| date = 2000| pages = 105\u20136}}</ref> According 2017 census, total district population is 1,356,774 of which 1,110,321 residing in rural area and 246,053 in urban area.\n\n==Administration==\nThe area around [[Nankana Sahib]] was formerly a [[tehsil]] of [[Sheikhupura District]].  In May 2005, the Punjab government decided to raise the status of [[Nankana Sahib]] to that of a district<ref>[http://archives.dawn.com/weekly/herald/herald48.htm District Profile: Central Punjab- Nankana Sahib - Dawn Pakistan]</ref> as a way of promoting development in the area, and investment from Indian Sikhs. {{fact|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Education ==\nDistrict Nankana Sahib is ranked at the 26th position in the education score index of the [[Pakistan District Education Rankings]] 2017 published by [[Alif Ailaan]]. The education score is composed of the learning score, retention score and gender parity score.\n\nIn the middle school infrastructure score index, which focuses on availability of basic facilities and the building condition of schools, Nankana Sahib ranks 51st. The facilities of electricity and drinking water in schools remain very good in the district with a 100% score. However, the building conditions are below average with a score of 45.07.\n\nOn the [https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074507/https://elections.alifailaan.pk/taleemdo-app/ TaleemDo! App], majority residents of several areas within Nankana Sahib have complained about shortage of teachers available for schools and there is no access of transport available to schools located at larger distances. This issue is reported by a majority of female students.\n\n==District development==\nThe possibility of the development of a university, named after Guru Nanak, has been raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/pak-govt-to-start-work-on-guru-nanak-varsity/544195/ |title=Pak govt to start work on Guru Nanak varsity at Nankana Sahib |publisher=Indian Express |date=2009-11-20 |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Punjab government decided to link Nankana Sahib District with the provincial capital, [[Lahore]].  With these plans the Punjab government is completing \"Khanqah Dogran Interchange\" (on the M-2) very swiftly, which is a helpful project to develop the newly created District of Nankana Sahib.  This will also give access to the Grand Trunk Road, which leads to the [[Indian Punjab]] from the [[Wagah]] border. Nankana Sahib-Amritsar bus was inaugurated by Ex-Prime Minister of India [[Manmohan Singh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabroadways.gov.in/amritsar-nankana-sahib.html |title=Department of Transport, Punjab, India |publisher=Punjabroadways.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Districts of Punjab (Pakistan)}}\n\n{{Administrative divisions of Nankana Sahib District}}\n\n[[Category:Districts of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Nankana Sahib District|*]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Nanak]]\n[[Category:Guru Nanak Dev]]\n[[Category:Sikh places]]\n[[Category:Sikhism in Pakistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Pakistani English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nankana Sahib\n| official_name           = \n| native_name             = {{Nastaliq|\u0636\u0650\u0644\u0639 \u0646\u0646\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06c1 \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628}}\n| native_name_lang        =\n| settlement_type         = [[Districts of Pakistan|District]]\n| image_skyline           = Pakistan - Punjab - Nankana Sahib.svg\n| imagesize               =\n| image_walt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_map               =\n| mapsize                 = 300px\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Map of Punjab (white) with Nankana Sahib District (Maroon).\n| coordinates             = {{coord|31.449561|73.70648|type:adm2nd_source:itwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Pakistan]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Pakistan|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]]\n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = [[Headquarters]]\n| seat           = [[Nankana Sahib]]\n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          = 2960\n| population_as_of        = 2017\n| population_footnotes    = <ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archivedate=2017-08-29}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 1,356,374\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| timezone1               = [[Time in Pakistan|PST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5\n| established_title       = Established\n| established_date        = May 2005\n| leader_title            = Hadhrat Khawajah Muhammad Sardar Ahmed Naqshbandi\n| blank_name              = [[Tehsil]]s\n| blank_info              = [[Nankana Sahib]]<br>[[Sangla Hill]]<br>[[Shah Kot Tehsil |Shah Kot]]\n| blank1_name_sec1         = District Council\n| blank1_info_sec1         = \n| demographics1_title1    = Main language(s)\n| demographics1_info1     = Punjabi, Urdu\n| website                 = <!-- DEAD LINK {{URL|http://www.nankana-sahib.gov.pk/|link}} -->\n}}\n\n'''Nankana Sahib District ''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0636\u0650\u0644\u0639 \u0646\u0646\u0643\u0627\u0646\u06c1 \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0650\u0628}}}})  is a [[Districts of Pakistan|district]] in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province of [[Pakistan]]. [[Nankana Sahib]] is the seat of the district government, and [[Shahkot, Pakistan|Shahkot]] is the largest urban center.  The district of Nankana Sahib is located about {{Convert|75|km|mi}} west of [[Lahore]] and about {{Convert|55|km|mi}} east of [[Faisalabad]]. Until 2005, it was part of [[Sheikhupura District]].\n\nAccording to the 1998 census results, the most widely spoken [[first language]]<ref>\"Mother tongue\": defined as the language of communication between parents and children.</ref> in the Nankana Sahib Tehsil was [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]], accounting for {{sigfig|98.58|3}}% of the population, while [[Urdu]] was the native language of {{sigfig|0.41|2}}%.<ref>{{Cite book| title = 1998 District Census report of Sheikhupura| location = Islamabad| publisher = Population Census Organization, Statistics Division, Government of Pakistan| series = Census publication | volume =  79| date = 2000| pages = 105\u20136}}</ref> According 2017 census, total district population is 1,356,774 of which 1,110,321 residing in rural area and 246,053 in urban area.\n\n==Administration==\nThe area around [[Nankana Sahib]] was formerly a [[tehsil]] of [[Sheikhupura District]].  In May 2005, the Punjab government decided to raise the status of [[Nankana Sahib]] to that of a district<ref>[http://archives.dawn.com/weekly/herald/herald48.htm District Profile: Central Punjab- Nankana Sahib - Dawn Pakistan]</ref> as a way of promoting development in the area, and investment from Indian Sikhs. {{fact|date=May 2016}}\n\n== Education ==\nDistrict Nankana Sahib is ranked at the 26th position in the education score index of the [[Pakistan District Education Rankings]] 2017 published by [[Alif Ailaan]]. The education score is composed of the learning score, retention score and gender parity score.\n\nIn the middle school infrastructure score index, which focuses on availability of basic facilities and the building condition of schools, Nankana Sahib ranks 51st. The facilities of electricity and drinking water in schools remain very good in the district with a 100% score. However, the building conditions are below average with a score of 45.07.\n\nOn the [https://web.archive.org/web/20180803074507/https://elections.alifailaan.pk/taleemdo-app/ TaleemDo! App], majority residents of several areas within Nankana Sahib have complained about shortage of teachers available for schools and there is no access of transport available to schools located at larger distances. This issue is reported by a majority of female students.\n\n==District development==\nThe possibility of the development of a university, named after Guru Nanak, has been raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/pak-govt-to-start-work-on-guru-nanak-varsity/544195/ |title=Pak govt to start work on Guru Nanak varsity at Nankana Sahib |publisher=Indian Express |date=2009-11-20 |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\nThe Punjab government decided to link Nankana Sahib District with the provincial capital, [[Lahore]].  With these plans the Punjab government is completing \"Khanqah Dogran Interchange\" (on the M-2) very swiftly, which is a helpful project to develop the newly created District of Nankana Sahib.  This will also give access to the Grand Trunk Road, which leads to the [[Indian Punjab]] from the [[Wagah]] border. Nankana Sahib-Amritsar bus was inaugurated by Ex-Prime Minister of India [[Manmohan Singh]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://punjabroadways.gov.in/amritsar-nankana-sahib.html |title=Department of Transport, Punjab, India |publisher=Punjabroadways.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2013-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Districts of Punjab (Pakistan)}}\n\n{{Administrative divisions of Nankana Sahib District}}\n\n[[Category:Districts of Punjab, Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Nankana Sahib District|*]]\n[[Category:2005 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Nanak]]\n[[Category:Guru Nanak Dev]]\n[[Category:Sikh places]]\n[[Category:Sikhism in Pakistan]]\n", "